(West mound - upper part of pit, but rather arbitrarily divided?) This is a fairly large unit, with bone preserved rather differently to anything yet seen on the East mound: some bones are very weathered, with deep cracks; some have salt encrustations on surface which has caused flaking and bone loss. Many fragments have exposed spongy bone through some sort of erosion. Other surfaces however are smooth and unweathered. There is some gnawing, some digestion, a little burning (mostly low temperature) and there are two fragments which are red in colour, almost looking as if they have been painted(?). Taxa: cattle, equids (large, which is interesting to know that E. caballus continued on until the Chalcolithic also), sheep, goat, dog (one tooth), a small carnivore (scapula). A cattle proximal metatarsal is very large. Cattle size; big chunks of long bone shaft (highly processed), rib, verts. For identified cattle, some postcranial but not much compared to sheep-sized, some loose teeth, and a large fragement of a large horn core (one of the few pieces completely burnt), along with lots of skull fragments. Equid is represented by quite a few phalanx 1s, and 2 astragali, and some loose teeth. In general, the bone material appears to derive from a variety of sources: some is heavily weathered, and some is well preserved; some exposed for carnivroe gnawing, some not. Since this unit may represent layers in the pit, could it be that some layers were covered quickly, and others were left more exposed? Or is the erosion some kind of result from the dungy nature of deposit (pot has green staining on, believed to be from dung). F97 = a cattle DNA sample (an os crochu) despite being washed and touched. D1 is a complete bone point. Flot sample 5 (1490) and Flot sample 1 (1313) 100% sorted. Only diagnostics recorded. The flot sample 5 is about 5-10% burned with a small amount of digestion. There is a lot of modern breakage, especially of the larger bones, but the prehistoric edges are sharp and abraded. Taxa include a few sheep/goat bones, a red deer intermediate phalanx and a cattle tooth. Flot sample 1 is very similar to flot 1. it is very even light brown, with little burning and almost no digestion. The material was rapidly buried and relatively undisturbed. The diagnostics are all sheep/goat except for one heavily burnt blob that might be a cattle patella. Last number = 320
Karen took a calculus sample from F252. F310 sampled for stable isotopes (CM/DCO 2010).
Louise Martin, (Nerissa Russell worked bone), Sheelagh Frame
